unknown as Scene, {\n      title: \'标题\',\n      message: \'消息\',\n      clo
seOnOverlay: true,\n      onCancel,\n    });\n    dialog.show();\n    const over
lay = (dialog as unknown as { overlay?: { emit: (event: string) => unknown } }).
overlay;\n    expect(overlay).toBeDefined();\n    overlay?.emit(\'pointerdown\')
;\n    expect(onCancel).toHaveBeenCalled();\n  });\n```\n\nThe overlay in UIDial
og is the same overlay created by UIPanel. But in UIDialog, at line 69, it does:
\n```typescript\nthis.overlay.removeAllListeners(\'pointerdown\');\nthis.overlay
.on(\'pointerdown\', () => this.cancel());\n```\n\nWait, but `this.overlay` is a
Phaser.GameObjects.Rectangle. In the mock, `removeAllListeners` and `on` are met
hods on MockContainer. But the mock\'s `removeAllListeners` removes from `this.e
vents`, while `on` adds to `this.events`. But `emit` on MockRectangle uses `emit
Event` from the global `eventHandlers` map, not `this.events`.\n\nWait, there\'s
a bug in the mock! Let me re-read the MockRectangle class:\n\n```typescript\ncla
ss MockRectangle extends MockImage {\n  // ...\n  on(event: string, handler: (..
.args: unknown[]) => void) {\n    recordEvent(this, event, handler);\n    return
this;\n  }\n  off(event: string, handler?: (...args: unknown[]) => void) {\n    
if (handler) {\n      removeEvent(this, event, handler);\n    } else {\n      co
nst keyPrefix = `${this.id}:`;\n      for (const key of eventHandlers.keys()) {\
n        if (key.startsWith(keyPrefix + event)) {\n          eventHandlers.delet
e(key);\n        }\n      }\n    }\n    return this;\n  }\n  removeAllListeners(
