ventHandlers.keys()) {\n      if (event) {\n        if (key.startsWith(keyPrefix
+ event)) {\n          eventHandlers.delete(key);\n        }\n      } else if (k
ey.startsWith(keyPrefix)) {\n        eventHandlers.delete(key);\n      }\n    }\
n    return this;\n  }\n  emit(event: string, ...args: unknown[]) {\n    emitEve
nt(this, event, ...args);\n    return this;\n  }\n}\n```\n\nSo `removeAllListene
rs(\'pointerdown\')` should clear all `pointerdown` handlers from the global `ev
entHandlers` map for this object. Then `on(\'pointerdown\', () => this.cancel())
` should add a new handler.\n\nBut wait - UIPanel also registers a `pointerdown`
handler on the overlay:\n```typescript\nthis.overlay.on(\'pointerdown\', () => {
\n  this.config.onOverlayClick?.();\n});\n```\n\nThen UIDialog removes all `poin
terdown` listeners and adds its own. In the mock, `removeAllListeners(\'pointerd
own\')` should remove the UIPanel\'s handler. Then `on(\'pointerdown\', ...)` ad
ds UIDialog\'s handler. Then when the test emits `pointerdown`, it should call `
cancel()`.\n\n`cancel()` calls `this.hide(() => { this.dialogConfig.onCancel?.()
})`.\n`hide()` creates a tween with `onComplete`. MockTweenManager calls `onComp
lete` synchronously. So `onCancel` should be called.\n\nWait, but the test faile
d saying `onCancel` was not called. Let me look more carefully...\n\nActually, l
ooking at the test output again:\n```\nFAIL src/ui/__tests__/UIDialog.test.ts > 
UIDialog > should close on overlay when closeOnOverlay is true\nAssertionError: 
expected "spy" to be called at least once\n```\n\nHmm, but wait. In the UIPanel 
`createOverlay`, the overlay is added to the scene directly, not to the panel. S
o when we do `dialog.show()`, it sets the panel visible, and also sets `this.ove
rlay.setVisible(true)`. But the overlay itself might not have the event handler 
properly set up in the mock.\n\nActually, I wonder if the issue is that `removeA
llListeners(\'pointerdown\')` in MockRectangle doesn\'t work correctly because t
he handler was added with `recordEvent` in `MockContainer.on`, but `MockRectangl
e` overrides `on` to use `recordEvent`. Wait, let me check:\n\nIn `MockContainer
`:\n```typescript\non(event: string, handler: (...args: unknown[]) => void) {\n 
if (!this.events[event]) this.events[event] = [];\n  this.events[event].push(han
dler);\n  return this;\n}\n```\n\nIn `MockRectangle`:\n```typescript\non(event: 
